      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A medium saucepan, a colander, and a large mixing bowl.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cook and cool the pasta",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cook {{pasta-dried}} of pasta in well-salted boiling water according to packet instructions until just al dente. Drain through a colander and rinse under cold running water until the pasta is completely cool. Shake off excess water.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the dressing",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Whisk {{olive-oil}} of olive oil with the lemon juice and zest, {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt, and {{black-pepper}} of black pepper in a large bowl.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Combine and serve",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the cooled pasta, drained tuna broken into chunks, cherry tomatoes, cucumber, {{capers}} of capers, and red onion to the bowl. Add the olives if using. Toss everything gently. Taste for salt and lemon, cold pasta needs more seasoning than warm pasta. Serve immediately or refrigerate for up to two days.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Add a drizzle more olive oil and toss again. The pasta will loosen as it absorbs the oil.",
              "cause": "Not enough dressing, or pasta dried out after draining.",
              "symptom": "Pasta is sticking together"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add more salt and a squeeze of lemon. The ratio will shift as it sits, refresh before serving.",
              "cause": "Cold pasta needs more seasoning than warm; the pasta also absorbs dressing as it sits.",
              "symptom": "Salad tastes flat"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add another tablespoon of olive oil. For next time, use tuna in olive oil and drain without pressing.",
              "cause": "Tuna in brine was used rather than oil, or it was pressed too dry.",
              "symptom": "Tuna is dry and crumbly"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Soak the sliced onion in cold water for 10 minutes before adding. This removes the sharpness without losing the flavour.",
              "cause": "Raw red onion can be very pungent.",
              "symptom": "Red onion is too sharp"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Tuna pasta salad sits alongside egg mayo sandwiches and prawn cocktail: popular, unfussy, eaten without a fuss. The Italian mix of tuna, oil, and capers, the same one used in tonnato sauces and antipasto plates, travelled into British home cooking through tinned tuna. Once dried pasta became a pantry staple in the 1980s, the cold pasta salad followed. The version here stays closer to its Italian roots than the mayo type that fills supermarket fridges.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
